  • Personally I hate making assumptions for CTF competitions and so figuring out what all these numbers and variables meant was hard even though I have a good understanding of circuits.
  • If you couldn't tell this was a circuit, you could have guessed by the name of the challenge, category, and by searching up OP AMP which is a component in the design.
  • I wasn't sure if these other components were capacitors, resistors, or inductors. There are valid reasons for all of them, capacitors have a more boxy design, R normally represents a resistor, and "I" could represent inductors.
  • I can safely assume that the sections with a R in their name represent a resistor since this is standard!
    • Connecting this with the important information section, tells me the value of the R1 and R2 values; 100 and 200 respectively.
    • But 100 what? 100 Ohms.....Or maybe Kilo Ohms. This is probably important to know.
    • Connecting the fact that the symbols used for the Units of R1 and R2 are used in the other components in the diagram, we can safely assume those components are resistors as well, but with a set value shown in the diagram.
      Units?

      There are 3 ways to figure out which units this circuit is in:

      1. Assume that since there are 2 symbols that it must be kOhms. Butttt, thats an assumption!
      2. Research and find out the fact that OpAmps tend to use resistor values in the 10,000's of Ohms and guess that 100 Ohms would probably be too little. But still a guess!
      3. Create the circuit using some kind of circuit software and test out the Vout value using Ohms and kOhms. This will give you the units for certain and it will allow for troubleshooting later. It is more work but it is the more secure way to do it! It is in KOhms btw.

Objective:

  • Now that we know what almost everything is in the diagram, we can now start trying to figure out how we get the flag. We still have 2 main unknowns......The purpose of the vout and what the b0,b1, bn-1, bn-2 information is.
    • Vout: Since this number is given, the safest assumption is that it is simply information that is given to aid in the process of finding the flag and thats kinda it.
    • Bn's: The information we are given about bn is that the logic high is 3.3V.
      • This tells me that these values are binary choice values. And that we will need to figure out which ones are on and which ones are off to get the desired vout!
        Confusion
        • Why are their only 4 of them then? and Why are some B0, and B1 and why are some Bn???
        • Maybe it was that I was tired during solving this challenge, but I didn't realize that the part shown below was meant to represent a n sized number of binary choices with the same circuit configuration repeated until I asked a mod what the * * * represented.

    Attention
    • If your like me, you wont know what the last part is right away and may need to spend countless hours trying to figure out how to reduce this part or at least understand what todo with it. I found the correct configuration by reverse image searching my circuit I drew on paper, and scrolled till I found the exact same configuration. That is when I learned about DAC, aka Digital to Analog Conversion!
  • DAC is the process where you convert binary data or signals into a Analog Wave signal using resistors and an OpAmp! After some googling you find out that the type of DAC for this design is a R-2R DAC configuration which is resembled by the 100 and 200 resistors respectively.
    Research
    • Using this website you can find more on DAC and find a formula to use to convert a set of binary bits to an Analog signal or a set voltage: https://www.electronics-tutorials.ws/combination/r-2r-dac.html
    • It is important to distinguish between formulas that give you the relationship between the output of the OpAmp and the Binary inputs vs the output of the entire Binary system and the binary Inputs. In our case either works as long as we use the correct variable values as inputs! I will use the 2nd option since that is the circuit we have and the circuit given in the link!
    • Here is the formula we have found:
      • This formula doesn't quite work for us yet. The article assumes possible variation in the choice of Input Voltages, But we know that if they are "on" then it will be 3.3V and that if it is "off" then it will be 0V. So we can simplify this equation by multiplying out 3.3V from each term in the numerator. I will show an example formula that is for a 4 bit system, to demonstrate how we will figure out how long our binary input is(I will use ):
      • : represents the binary choice of each bit.
    Bug
    • Dividing the 3.3 works mathematically, but we are dealing with a ctf challenge which likely uses programming languages to calculate the Vout value and likely has some kind of rounding or truncating happening. This is important because if we do multiply out the 3.3 we are assuming that 3.3 exists perfectly inside each binary section and the reality is it doesn't in this case. If you multiply out the 3.3 you will get the flag format and then the error will propagate and you will begin getting garbage even though mathematically it is correct.
    • We can divide over the 3.3 to the other side and replace with since we know they are the same. We will also simplify the formula to be more digestible:
      • If you know anything about Decimal to binary conversion, This tells us a lot about our DAC. It tells us that each bit has a set value of the final Vout value and it increases as the bits move to the right and become More Significant.
    Important
    • This is the same as Decimal to Binary except the bits are least significant on the right and most significant on the left. Because of this property we can use the same strategy of converting Decimal to Binary to convert to Binary values.
    • We just have to check if the value is divisible by the Most Significant Bit which is 0.5 in this case and if it is, subtract the value and test the next bit out. If the value is not divisible by the bit then move on to the next bit!

Programming

  • Now we just have to program it.....Easier said then done. Our original Vout value is very large and the calculations need to be precise.
    Note
    • We will not be dividing the 3.3 over in the above step for the programming! This is explained in the Bug section above!
    • We will instead multiply 3.3 for each binary choice as originally shown in the formula.
  • I recommend using libraries such as Numpy, Decimal, and maybe use SageMath as a whole on CoCalc to aid the process.
    Protip

    Use Numpy for large numbers!
    Use Decimal for long Floating Point precision!

  1. Import libraries, modules, setup precision, and setup Variables:
    • Decimal works by adding the precision when arithmetic is done, not when Coverting to the decimal type(Documentation: https://docs.python.org/3/library/decimal.html.
      • Decimal(3.14) is equal to whatever it was before(float) but now its a decimal type: "3.140000000000000124344978758017532527446746826171875"
      • Decimal('3.14') is equal to exactly 3.14: "3.14"
from decimal import * # Imports all of decimal library

getcontext().prec = 1000 # Sets precision to an absurd number

# Make Original Vout value a Decimal Datatype
Vout = Decimal('1.0100160293633633097836165218520645928533165673701591638847239768412297771673628701675769728865523783884907827854645836850813325581348710325049612453127737826117688733914936444315081605041365932902096')

output_binary = "" # Sets a string where the binary will be placed.

# Gets an exact value for leftside of equation.
Vdac = (Vout * 5) / 3
  1. Setup loop to test binary values up to a large number and Add If else statement to test for divisibility:
for n in range(0,500): # Loop through 500 binary positions
	# Tests for Divisability via subtraction
    div = Vdac - Decimal((3.3 * 1)/2**n) # Don't Forget to Convert Float to Decimal
    if(div > 0): # Checks if bit was divisible
        Vdac = div # If so, updates value for next bit
        output_binary += "1" # Adds a on bit to the output
    else:
        output_binary += "0" # Else adds a off bit to the output
  1. Output the Flag by converting the binary string to bytes
    • a bytestring or an bytearray are basically ASCII values or ASCII represented via hex. It is different than a string because anything can be put inside of a string regardless if it is ASCII!
    • The general idea is that you need to loop through the binary and take 8 bits and convert them into an interger value and then into bytes aka ascii.
    • Here is a way to do it in one line(There is a better way todo it using python3 but it wont work here for some reason(https://stackoverflow.com/a/32683047/4279)):
      Coverting Binary String to byteString
      • bytes(int(output_binary[i : i + 8], 2) for i in range(0, len(output_binary), 8)) ​
print(bytes(int(output_binary[i : i + 8], 2) for i in range(0, len(output_binary), 8)))

Here is the entire Solution:

from decimal import *

getcontext().prec = 1000

Vout = Decimal('1.0100160293633633097836165218520645928533165673701591638847239768412297771673628701675769728865523783884907827854645836850813325581348710325049612453127737826117688733914936444315081605041365932902096')

Vdac = (Vout * 5) / 3

output_binary =""

for n in range(0,500):
    div = Vdac - Decimal((3.3 * 1)/2**n)
    if(div > 0):
        Vdac = div
        output_binary += "1"
    else:
        output_binary += "0"

print(bytes(int(output_binary[i : i + 8], 2) for i in range(0, len(output_binary), 8)))
